Sectoral output differentials measure the levels of inter-elite conflict. In other words, \autoref{fig:incometax} operationalizes the degree in which the agricultural sector was ``challenged'' (or not) by an incipient industrial sector. %As we explain below, political monopolies were terminated when the levels of inter-sectoral equality were high. Given the structural transformations these cases went through, they were able to develop ``strong'' state institutions and competitive oligarchic political systems. However, when inter-sectoral equality was low, that is when the agricultural sector kept dominating since colonial period through the 19th and 20th centuries, political resources were oriented to prioritize policy goods for the agricultural sector.
We build on theories that claim that economic and political competition (or the lack of) have a positive (or negative) impact on state capacities. For example, \citet[481]{Kurtz2009} argues that where ``no faction can easily become permanently dominant'', state capacities should be higher. Similarly, \citet{Geddes1991} argues that competition between two rival parties of about the same size create the incentives to invest in political institutions. \citet[40]{Cardenas2010} in his formal and empirical models also finds that ``concentration of political and economic power reduces the incentives to invest in state capacity''. However, he models inequality between \emph{elites} and \emph{citizens}. We expand on this idea by modeling the period \emph{before} full democratization existed and also by modeling the interest of two types of elites. This paper also builds on theories on the sectoral origins of income taxation. As development economists argue, there is an intrinsic sectoral conflict between the two sectors regarding generation of income and its potential taxation. For example, \citet[55]{Best1976}, argues that ``the sectoral origin of income is an important determinant of tax potential [...] the agricultural sectors in Central America preclude[d] effective income taxation''. Similarly, \citet[]{Mares2015} study how income taxation in Europe is associated to between-elites conflicts, particularly between the landed elite and the industrial elite\footnote{However, state-capacities are tangentially studied.}. Taxation and state formation has been studied in Africa too. For example, \citet{SanchezdelaSierra2014} studies the relationship between taxation and state formation in Eastern Congo. This paper elaborates on these insights by tracing the \emph{political origins} of income taxation. As argued later in the paper, economic equality paired with political inequality introduced endogenous incentives to build both \emph{state} and \emph{democratic} institutions. 


Intra-elite (in)equality and regime type plays a fundamental role in our argument. There have been important recent contributions lately (see for example \citet[Ch. 9]{Acemoglu:1996rm} and  \citet[]{Ansell:2014ty}). Building on this literature, we introduce the state capacities question. Our findings are consistent with \citet[9]{Rueschemeyer:1992}, in that ``[c]onsolidation of state power was an essential prerequisite for democratization''. One of our main contributions is the idea that inter-elite political inequality paired with inter-elite economic equality plays a fundamental role in political/institutional development. \citet[]{Garfias2015} finds in M\'exico the exact opposite: \emph{unequal} relative distribution of political and economical power causes state formation. The proposed mechanism is that ruling elites, taking advantage of their transitory strengthened  position, expropriate weaker elites and send bureaucrats to control local weakened bosses (his proxy for state capacities). We find that political monopolies were broken when the excluded industrial sector gained economic leverage.% that allowed them to bargain better political and economical conditions.

